      "writtenOn": "2017-06-27T09:57:08Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "After thinking about this code some more, I think the math may be wrong here and will overweight the interior pixels and underweight the edge. Assume an (approximated and non-normalized) 5-element Gaussian kernel of 1 4 5 4 1. If we\u0027re processing the leftmost pixel, the \u00275\u0027 will be centered on the leftmost pixel. This will give the pixels a weight of 5/10, 4/10, and 1/10. They should really be (1 + 4 + 5)/15 \u003d 10/15, 4/15 and 1/15.",
      "revId": "d2877a45a2636be54405fc5576c516e3313361da",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
      "unresolved": true
    },
    {
      "key": {
        "uuid": "a6d6f281_977f1806",
        "filename": "src/gpu/effects/GrGaussianConvolutionFragmentProcessor.cpp",
        "patchSetId": 4
      },
      "lineNbr": 106,
      "author": {
        "id": 7520
      },
      "writtenOn": "2017-06-27T16:44:52Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "You are right. In my fix, I just simply re-weight the kernel in-bounds.\n\nYour method should be the correct clamping to edge mode.\nI tried your original method: coord.%s \u003d clamp(coord.%s, bounds.x, bounds.y), but it seems does not give a desired result. I will try again to see why. Or I can manually calculate the value here: 1) get bounds_x_value, bounds_y_value. 2) if coord.direction \u003c bounds.x, then color +\u003d bounds_x_value. 3) if coord.direction \u003e bounds.y, then color +\u003d bounds_y_value. 4) others, use current code.",
      "parentUuid": "b8f872ac_9b217b14",
      "revId": "d2877a45a2636be54405fc5576c516e3313361da",
      "serverId": "5086850b-e599-37d2-8ec8-ff16aeccbf02",
